From a258d64dfc054bb37e0fe96a8e5728dfb05b7b41 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: SlayZone Dev <dev@slayzone.local>
Date: Sat, 18 Apr 2026 07:38:47 +0200
Subject: [3/7] slayzone: sidecar client C++ shim (Phase 2.3)
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Browser-process client for the Bun sidecar (Phase 3 still WIP).
Speaks LSP-framed JSON-RPC 2.0 over a Unix domain socket at
\$SLAYZONE_RUNTIME_DIR/sidecar.sock; platform default is
~/Library/Application Support/SlayZone/run/sidecar.sock on macOS and
\$XDG_RUNTIME_DIR/slayzone/sidecar.sock on Linux. Windows (named pipe)
is not wired in Phase 2 by design.

Design notes:
- Dedicated Slayzone.Sidecar base::Thread owns the socket. Blocking
  recv in a PostTask loop; Phase 3 swaps for FileDescriptorWatcher
  once graceful mid-read shutdown matters.
- Connect is non-blocking via a one-shot timer that fires the next
  ScheduleConnect; backoff starts at 500 ms and caps at 30 s.
- Keepalive sends sidecar.ping every 30 s on an open connection;
  disconnect detected by recv EOF / send failure drops pending
  callbacks with an empty dict and enters the reconnect loop.
- Pending callbacks live in a flat_map<int64_t, ResponseCallback>
  keyed by the JSON-RPC id; response matches invoke on the IO
  thread. Phase 3.6 proxy consumers should bind_post_task to return
  to their own sequence.
- Startup handshake: slayzone.SidecarClient::Start is called from
  BrowserProcessImpl::Init() as early as possible. The first thing
  the thread does is LOG(INFO) the resolved socket path and log
  each connect attempt — that's the "sidecar handshake logs
  visible" exit criterion for Phase 2.

- chrome/browser/slayzone/sidecar_client.{h,cc}: new. ~400 LoC.
- chrome/browser/BUILD.gn: sources wired into the `browser` target.
- chrome/browser/browser_process_impl.cc: Start in Init(),
  Stop in StartTearDown(). Guarded by !IS_ANDROID since Phase 2
  doesn't target mobile.
